project.title: Portland-Vancouver Regional Eco-Blitz
project.description: Find out more at http:////www.theintertwine.org//blitz.Be part of a new, citizen science movement & Identify area species to contribute to the regions species inventory.  Whether there is a need for baseline data to support a conservation program or just out of curiosity, we often wonder about the various lifeforms around us .  There are numerous surveys done throughout the area, but sometimes the resulting data is not accessible or does not translate for the general public.  The Eco-Blitz Series serves to establish continuous species ID events, bringing partners together from all over to make this data transparent and accessible to all.  This is done by displaying the real-time data on this website.  This effort aims to:rnrn•tRaise awareness of biodiversityrn•tGenerate appreciation of natural resourcesrn•tEstablish a shared effort among science professionals, educators, and the general publicrn rnThis is a collaborative effort among the following organizations with ongoing events:  Cascade Education Corps, City of Portland, City of Vancouver, Clark County, Clean Water Services, Get To Know, iNaturalist, Jackson Bottom Wetlands, Johnson Creek Watershed Council, Lower Columbia Estuary Partnership, Oregon Metro, Oregon SOLVE, The Intertwine, The National Park Service, The Wetlands Conservancy, Tualatin Hills Parks & Recreation District, YMCArn

taxon.wikipedia_summary: The <b>Douglas squirrel<//b> (<i>Tamiasciurus douglasii<//i>) is a pine squirrel found in the Pacific coastal states of the United States as well as the southwestern coast of British Columbia in Canada. It is sometimes known as the <b>chickaree<//b> or <b>pine squirrel<//b>, although these names are also used for the American red squirrel. Variant spellings of the common name are <b>Douglas squirrel<//b> and <b>Douglass squirrel<//b>. The Native Americans of Kings River called it the Pillillooeet

taxon.name: Annelida
taxon.wikipedia_summary: The <b>annelids<//b> (Annelida, from Latin <i>anellus<//i>, little ring), also known as the <b>ringed worms<//b> or <b>segmented worms<//b>, are a large phylum, with over 17,000 extant species including ragworms, earthworms, and leeches. The species exist in and have adapted to various ecologies – some in marine environments as distinct as tidal zones and hydrothermal vents, others in fresh water, and yet others in moist terrestrial environments.

taxon.name: Clitellata
taxon.wikipedia_summary: The <b>Clitellata<//b> are a class of annelid worms, characterized by having a clitellum - the collar that forms a reproductive cocoon during part of their life cycles. The <b>clitellates<//b> comprise around 8,000 species. Unlike the class of Polychaeta, they do not have parapodia and their heads are less developed.

project.description: In celebration of the 50th anniversary of Oregons Beach Bill, the landmark legislation passed in 1967 that protects the publics right to access the coastline, Oregon State Parks has created their first-ever citizen-science species inventory.  Focusing on all of Oregons coastal state parks, the inventory will further our knowledge, understanding, and appreciation of species richness and diversity along the Oregon Coast.  rnrn
